<p><b>What are the disadvantages of a JCT contract?</b> What are the disadvantages of using a JCT contract? When a JCT contract is created, it can be difficult for either party to modify their needs. Given the usual format of JCT contracts, any alterations could result in project delays due to the introduction of unfamiliarity.</p>
<p><b>Why choose JCT?</b> JCT contracts are produced to provide two key services: Minimise the transaction cost of entering into a contract. Provide benchmark provisions in standard form contracts.</p>
<p><b>What is FIDIC and JCT?</b> Delay analysis in construction contracts, such as those based on FIDIC (International Federation of Consulting Engineers) and JCT (Joint Contracts Tribunal) standard forms, is a process used to determine the causes and extent of project delays and their impact on the contractual obligations of the parties involved.</p>
<p><b>What is the JCT standard for?</b> The JCT Standard Building Contract is designed for large or complex construction projects where detailed contract provisions are needed. Standard Building Contracts are suitable for projects procured via the traditional or conventional method.</p>
<p><b>Do I need a JCT?</b> We recommend that you put in place a JCT contract. You don't have to and your decision may hinge on the relative complexity and cost of the construction. They first appeared in 1931 and are useful for protecting the client and contractor in writing in case of delays, disputes or unexpected price hikes.</p>
<p><b>What is the JCT standard form of building contract 2016?</b> The employer must provide drawings together with a description of works, and either a specification or work schedules at tender stage. The project is generally not complex enough to require bills of quantities.</p>
<p><b>What are JCT recitals?</b> The JCT agreement comprises of the following sections: The Recitals: sets the project overview background, brief description of works and design portion if applicable. The Articles: Identifies the primary obligations of the parties under the contract.</p>